  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Gambia: Documenting human rights violations under Jammeh&apos;s regime</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Since March 2018, HURICAP has been working to build the capacity of a local human rights organisation in the Gambia. The local partner is a CSO that was established in 2017, right after Gambia&#x2019;s transition to democracy with the role to mobilize victims of the former regime in order for them to play an active role in the transitional justice (TJ) process in the country. The latter started with the adoption of the Truth, Reconciliation and Reparations Committee (TRRC) Act in to address atrocities during Yahya Jammeh&#x2019;s 22 years&#x2019; rule. This is seen as crucial for Gambia&#x2019;s transition to a culture of democracy, rule of law and human rights.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Gambia is a small country in West Africa that for 22 years was subordinated to the repressive rule of Yahya Jammeh. In December 2016, Jammeh was defeated by Adama Barrow, who led the country&#x2019;s political transition. The new government has been committed to reforming several repressive laws and reforming the security forces. Moreover, a transitional justice process has been launched to seek truth, reconciliation and reparations for its victims and ultimately to bring perpetrators of human rights violations under Jammeh&apos;s rule to account for their wrongdoings.</narrative>
  </description>
